85":"1185","1260":"1260","1183":"1183","1280":"1280","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gordon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Gordon in Berwickshire, named with Welsh <i>gor</i> ‘spacious’ + <i>din</i> ‘fort’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Gourdon in Saône-et-Loire, so called from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Gordus</i> + the locative suffix <i>-o</i>, <i>-ōnis</i>.","English (of Norman origin): alternatively, said to be a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>gourd</i> ‘heavy, dull, sluggish’ (compare 8 below)."],"variants":[{"name":"Gordin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eyal, Moisey, Yakov, Zalman, Erez, Faina, Haya, Mendel.  Russian Leonid, Aleksandr, Boris, Feiga, Genady.","Jewish (from Russia): variant of   Gordon   5.","French: variant of   Gourdin  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Gordon was born in 1214, in Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Thomas de Gordon, Knight, 3rd Laird of Gordon, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Thomas De Gordon, was 29. He married Marjorie of Aberdeenshire about 1228, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 28 August 1259, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1214–28 August 1259":"1214–28. august 1259","1214–1259":"1214–1259","1198–Female":"1198–Surnud","1234–1280":"1234–1280","1183–1260":"1183–1260","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1259":"1259","1214":"1214","about 1228":"umbes 1228","28 August 1259":"28. august 1259","1234":"1234","1198":"1198","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1183":"1183","1280":"1280","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1214–28 August 1259":"1214–28. elokuuta 1259","1214–1259":"1214–1259","1198–Female":"1198–Kuollut","1234–1280":"1234–1280","1183–1260":"1183–1260","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1214":"1214","about 1228":"noin 1228","28 August 1259":"28. elokuuta 1259","1234":"1234","1198":"1198","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1183":"1183","1280":"1280","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Kelso, Roxburghshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1214–28 August 1259":"1214–28 août 1259","1214–1259":"1214–1259"